MiniMart — full business case scenario inventory

Every scenario below traces to specific rule IDs in BUSINESS_RULES.md. Nothing
here introduces new business behavior — this is the complete API-surface
reading of the rules already locked, expanding on the seven scenarios
(A–G) identified earlier for the database proof (Archive/Development/Database-Scripts/Sequence),
which were scoped to what a one-shot data-seeding pass needed, not to the
full set of things the backend must actually expose. Those seven map onto
this list as noted below. Phase files under Phase/ group these scenarios
into a delivery order; this file is the reference they cite back to.

--- identity-service ---

1.  Register a Customer account.
    ACC-001, ACC-002, ACC-003, ACC-004

2.  Log in successfully.
    ACC-005 (success path), ACC-006

3.  Fail to log in — wrong password, or an email that isn't registered at
    all — both reported identically.
    ACC-005

4.  View own profile.
    ACC-011

5.  Update own profile (name only).
    ACC-011

6.  Administrator views any account (support).
    ACC-011

7.  Administrator deactivates an account.
    ACC-006, ACC-007, ACC-008
    (= Scenario F's identity-side action, Database-Scripts step 17)

8.  Administrator reactivates a previously deactivated account.
    ACC-006, ACC-008 — see Discussion/Stage-1 Q2 for what this does and
    doesn't change.

9.  Administrator promotes an account to Administrator.
    ACC-009, ACC-010

10. System bootstrap — exactly one Administrator exists before any
    customer has registered.
    ACC-010
    (= Scenario A, Database-Scripts step 05)

--- catalog-service ---

11. Administrator creates a product.
    CAT-001, CAT-002, CAT-003, CAT-004, CAT-006
    (= Scenario B, Database-Scripts step 06)

12. Anyone browses/searches the catalog — Deactivated products excluded,
    zero-stock products still shown and marked out of stock.
    CAT-006, CAT-007, CAT-008, CAT-011

13. Administrator edits a product's price, name, description, or category.
    CAT-010 — only future orders are affected; past orders keep their
    ORD-005 snapshot regardless.

14. Administrator deactivates a product.
    CAT-008
    (part of Scenario B, Database-Scripts step 06)

15. Administrator removes a product outright (only ever legal for a
    product that has never been part of any order) vs. attempts to remove
    one that has (must be blocked — deactivate instead).
    CAT-009

--- order-service ---

16. Customer places an order with one or more line items (happy path).
    ORD-001, ORD-002, ORD-003, ORD-004, ORD-005, ORD-006, ORD-008, ORD-009
    (= Scenario D, Database-Scripts steps 08–10)

17. Checkout is rejected because at least one line item can't be fully
    satisfied — the whole order is rejected, nothing is partially
    deducted.
    ORD-007, GEN-001, CAT-007
    (= Scenario G, Database-Scripts step 18)

18. The same checkout is submitted twice (double-click / network retry) —
    only one order ever exists.
    ORD-009
    (proved as a guardrail in Scenario H, Database-Scripts step 19)

19. Customer views their own orders / order history.
    ORD-013

20. Administrator views any customer's orders (support).
    ORD-013

21. Customer cancels their own order while it's Placed.
    ORD-010, ORD-011, ORD-012
    (= Scenario E, Database-Scripts steps 11–13)

22. Customer attempts to cancel an order that isn't theirs, or is already
    Cancelled — rejected.
    ORD-011

23. A customer's account is later deactivated — their past orders remain
    exactly as they were, still attributed to them.
    ORD-014, ACC-007
    (= Scenario F, Database-Scripts steps 14–17)

--- notification-service ---

24. An order is successfully placed — a notification is recorded for the
    buyer.
    NTF-001
    (part of Scenario D, Database-Scripts step 10)

25. An order is cancelled — a notification is recorded for the buyer.
    NTF-002
    (part of Scenario E, Database-Scripts step 13)

26. Customer views their own notification history.
    NTF-003

27. Administrator views any customer's notifications (support).
    NTF-003

28. Recording a notification fails — the order/cancellation that
    triggered it is unaffected; already-final, not rolled back.
    NTF-005

--- Global, cross-cutting (not separate endpoints, but must hold across
    every scenario above) ---

- All monetary values are one fixed currency, no conversion. GEN-002
- All records (accounts, products, orders, notifications) are retained
  indefinitely — no scenario above ever hard-deletes an account, order, or
  notification. GEN-003
